snippet.textDisplay:
Rajasthani Part Meaning
Baisara Beera means Brother of my Sister in law. In Past times traditinally Rajasthani women never call their hasbands by their name.

Wife: O my brother of my sister in law (Baisara Beera)take me to my home (fathers) I miss my home( Exact menaning in Hindi:Mujhe Ghar ki yaad aa rahi hai)

Husband: o my beautiful wife why are you upset here (Hindi: saas ke ghar me tumhe kya dukh hai)

Wife: mother in law ask me

to fetch water... my delicate waist get sprain...

Husband: for this work i will appoint a servant..your delicate waist should not get stressed...then it will not get sprain 

Wife: your sister talks to me in a bad way..i cant bear this ... plz my husband drop me to my homeee...I miss my own home 

Husband : my sister is like a cuckoo bird. She is here for few days then she will fly away. 

Wife: you are just fooling me..i cant make u understand ..i

want to go home..i miss my homeee

snippet.textDisplay: It's already a shame that we do not have enough songs from a talent like Kalpana Patowary in the mainstream. My mom and I listen to her Bhojpuri folk songs in sheer delight and cannot stop complimenting the feel and the 'rass' in her voice. India really needs to look beyond film music to identify with the richness of its heritage and folklore.
snippet.textOriginal: It's already a shame that we do not have enough songs from a talent like Kalpana Patowary in the mainstream. My mom and I listen to her Bhojpuri folk songs in sheer delight and cannot stop complimenting the feel and the 'rass' in her voice. India really needs to look beyond film music to identify with the richness of its heritage and folklore.
